{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488443"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:42:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:42:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"446"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/446"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.1,0.12,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"446"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92379"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/446"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"446"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75684"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"405"},{"type":"tags","id":"1131"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31538"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31539"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92379"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old cleaner presents to the Emergency Department with a three day history of gradually worsening left knee pain. She denies any history of trauma. She is able to mobilise but with difficulty.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 118/72 mmHg, pulse 70/min and temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. The anterior aspect of the left knee is swollen, warm and tender to touch. There is no joint line tenderness, with intact range of motion. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prepatellar bursitis","Septic arthritis","Patellar tendonitis","Osteoarthritis","Stress fracture"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFormerly known as \u0022housemaid\u0027s knee\u0022, \u003Cstrong\u003Eprepatellar bursitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a problem commonly experienced by people who spend a lot of time kneeling or putting pressure on their knees. This patient\u2019s occupation as a cleaner makes this likely as does the predominance of signs are on the anterior aspect of the knee. Septic arthritis would show constitutional symptoms such as fever and a significantly impaired range of motion secondary to pain. Although possible, osteoarthritis would be less likely in a 35-year-old. Additionally, the three day history and inflammatory features on examination would make this diagnosis very unlikely. The short history would also reduce the likelihood of a stress fracture. Patellar tendinitis is a good differential in this case. However, this typically develops due to a reasonably significant period of repetitive strain and overload in youth athletic individuals. The timeline and occupation would therefore point more towards prepatellar bursitis.\u00a0\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Prepatellar bursitis is a common complaint amongst those who spend a lot of time on their knees."],"references":["Baumbach SF, Lobo CM, Badyine I, et al. Prepatellar and olecranon bursitis: literature review and development of a treatment algorithm. Arch Orthop Trauma Surg 2014; 134:359-70."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75684"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"446"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"expl